  "texts": [
    "(Equivalently, one may define adM as the vector bundle associated to the (Aut(N) ⋉ N)-principal bundle P → B via the representation (8).)",
    "Let V:= ker dπ be the vertical distribution on M. The key property of the adjoint bundle, which holds by construction, is that local sections of adM are in one-to-one correspondence with invariant sections of V, i.e.",
    "vertical invariant vector fields on M. More generally, the same is true for sections of tensor products of adM and the corresponding invariant tensor fields on M.Notice also that an isomorphism of twisted principal bundles f: M 1 → M 2 maps vertical invariant fields onto vertical invariant fields, thus inducing a vector bundle map f ad: adM 1 → adM 2 that preserves the Lie algebra structure of the fibres.There is a straightforward generalisation of the notion of principal connection to this setting:Definition 2.6.",
    "A connection on a twisted principal bundle π:M → B is an invariant distribution H ⊂ T M complementary to V = ker dπ.Precisely as in the principal bundle setting, one may equivalently view a connection as the kernel of an invariant, V-valued one-form on M. Its restriction to each trivialisation U i × N is an 𝔫-valued one-form satisfying the usual properties of a principal connection.",
    "In this article, connections will often arise as orthogonal complements of V ⊂ T M with respect to some invariant metric.An important feature of a connection H ⊂ T M is its holonomy."
  ],
